WEBVTT

00:00.031 --> 00:00.692
win-win.

00:02.314 --> 00:08.744
So this paper is about semi-supervised learning in effect.

00:08.764 --> 00:14.432
So it's at the intersection actually of semi-supervised learning, knowledge distillation and transfer learning.

00:14.853 --> 00:17.597
So what do we mean by semi-supervised learning?

00:17.717 --> 00:21.162
Usually in supervised learning you'll have some sort of data set

00:21.142 --> 00:25.792
And the dataset will contain, let's say it's an image net, it's image dataset.

00:26.193 --> 00:27.936
So the dataset will contain images.

00:28.658 --> 00:31.945
This is an image with like some sort of cat on it.

00:32.947 --> 00:36.755
And it will contain the labels according to that.

00:36.935 --> 00:38.138
So cat.

00:38.118 --> 00:45.184
Now, in semi-supervised learning, you assume that, so this is supervised learning.

00:45.405 --> 00:50.709
In semi-supervised learning, you assume that only part of your dataset has the labels.

00:51.130 --> 00:57.856
So like only this part down here has the labels, and the upper part does not have the labels.

00:58.256 --> 01:00.018
So that's semi-supervised learning.

01:00.298 --> 01:07.264
It's often the case when it's very expensive to get labels, so you can only get labels for a couple of images in your dataset.

01:07.244 --> 01:11.850
But very often in semi-supervised learning, you still assume it's the same data set.

01:12.491 --> 01:16.176
There is a slightly different setup here that's called transfer learning.

01:17.178 --> 01:23.847
So in transfer learning, what you'll have is you'll have your data set that has the labels, but it's very small.

01:24.287 --> 01:26.090
So you'll notice I've drawn it smaller.

01:26.390 --> 01:27.852
That means you have very little.

01:27.832 --> 01:35.406
That is also the case when it's very expensive to get labels, but also it's expensive to get the data itself.

01:35.767 --> 01:46.667
This is often the case, like say in medical data, where not only is it expensive to get labels for like a CT scan, it's actually expensive to get the CT scan.

01:46.647 --> 01:57.751
So, what the goal in transfer learning is, is to say, well, I do, I do have only this small data set, but I do have this giant other data set over here.

01:58.232 --> 02:06.951
Now, can't I, it's not the same, it's maybe they're not CT, so these are CT scans, maybe these are x-rays, right?

02:06.931 --> 02:09.897
They're fairly similar, similar technology.

02:11.159 --> 02:14.445
If you slice the CT, it'll give you sort of an x-ray.

02:15.006 --> 02:23.202
Can I pre-train my model on x-ray data and then fine-tune it on the CT data?

02:23.182 --> 02:26.810
So that's called transfer learning, usually.

02:27.210 --> 02:30.437
Now, this can be done with or without labels.

02:30.457 --> 02:35.568
So it can be that for the xray dataset, you do have the labels or you don't have the labels.

02:35.608 --> 02:39.115
There are techniques for all of those.

02:39.697 --> 02:40.819
Now,

02:40.799 --> 02:44.885
What we're going to look at today is kind of the situation right here.

02:45.186 --> 02:52.797
It's the transfer learning situation where you do not have the labels for this x-ray data set.

02:53.218 --> 03:05.997
But other than in this x-ray example, what we're going to look at is the small data set is going to be our ImageNet database, so our original picture with label database.

03:05.977 --> 03:15.459
So you'll see immediately the difference here is that in the transfer learning setting, we usually assume that the data set we want to train on is fairly small.

03:15.900 --> 03:20.290
Here, you know, ImageNet is already sizable.

03:21.620 --> 03:28.390
But what we have is we have a much larger database of unlabeled images that we can just get from the internet.

03:28.890 --> 03:34.799
So we can scrape the internet for any kind of pictures, and that will be our unlabeled dataset.

03:35.139 --> 03:43.611
And what we'll try to do is somehow incorporate this unlabeled dataset here into the training process to get better on the ImageNet dataset.

03:43.591 --> 03:54.287
Okay, so this is the problem statement is you have the ImageNet dataset and you have a second much larger dataset of unlabeled images and you somehow want to make use of them.

03:54.708 --> 03:57.893
So I hope you see how this is sort of connected to the others.

03:57.953 --> 04:11.674
It's essentially sort of a transfer semi-supervised learning setting, but with the exception that usually in transfer learning you assume that the labeled dataset is like super small.

04:11.654 --> 04:13.096
which is not the case here.

04:13.317 --> 04:17.323
And that's going to result in us being able to apply a different technique.

04:17.704 --> 04:20.629
So this different technique is called the noisy student.

04:21.631 --> 04:28.262
Now, usually what you might do in a transfer learning setting is you might want to start with that big data set, right?

04:28.642 --> 04:34.111
Because that's the data set that's sizable enough to allow you to train a really big model on it.

04:34.191 --> 04:37.978
And then you fine tune and you sort of hope that the information transfers over.

